--## SQL INTRODUCTION --
--RDBMS was introduced in 1980, from there in 2010s cloud based platforms.
--In 2014 Snowflake was introduced...
--Computerised DB system were introduced in 1960s.
--RDMS like oracle,SQL server (Microsoft), DB2 (IBM) -> 1980s
--RDMS-> data are stored in form of rows and coloumns (i.e. Tables) and related data are stored in different tables and linked using redundnat values.
--Coloumns: An individual piece of data.
--Row: A Set of related of coloumns.
--Table: A sets of rows.
--Primary Key: One or more coloumns that can be used as a unique identifer for each row in a table.
--Foreign Key: One or more coloumns that can be used together to identify a single row in another table.
--Normalization: The process of designing a DB to ensure that each indepent piece of information is in only one place (except for foregin Keys).
--SQL: Structured Query Language, it was orignally developed for quering/retriving and manupulating the data in relational databases. It is evolved to handle complex data such as JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) or other documents allowing integration b/w SQL and procedural languages such as python.
--SQL command categories: 
    --> Schema Statements (data definiton language (DDL)): Creating & modifying DB structure; ex: Create table, Create Index, Alter Table.
    -->Data Statement (Data Manupulation Language (DML)): Quering and manupulating data. ex: select,insert,update,delete,merge.
    -->Transaction Statements (Transaction controled language (TCL)): creating & ending transations. ex: commit,rollback.
--SQL is a non-procedural language; meaning that you define waht you want done, but not how to do it.
--SQL SCRIPTING: To fill a gap of procedural language(Python, Java) with constructs(looping, conditional statement) to SQL. Ex: ORACLE->PL/SQL , MICROSOFT->TRANSACT-SQL. Snowflake provides snowflake-scripting-language (SnowSL), which allows user to declare variables, incorporate loopings, conditional statements,detect and hadle exceptions.

